uthorization2star  aThe New Institutionalism in Education brings together leading academics to explore the ongoing changes in K–12 and higher education in both the United States and abroad. The contributors show that current educational trends—including the increased globalization of education, the growing emphasis on educational markets and school choice, the rise of accountability systems, and the persistent influence of business groups like textbook manufacturers and test makers on educational policy—can best be understood when observed through an institutional lens. Because schools and universities are organizations that are stabilized by deeply institutionalized rules, they are subject to the enduring problem of substantive educational reform. This book gives researchers and policy analysts conceptual tools and empirical assessments to gauge the possibilities for institutional reform and innovation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEducational sociology. 0aInstitutions (Philosophy). 0aSchool management and organizationxPhilosophy. 4aEducation : Comparative Education. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aAurini, Janice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, David P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernasconi, Andrés, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBidwell, Charles E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurch, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevy, Daniel C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyer, Heinz-Dieter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyer, Hei